00:57.440 --> 00:59.880
In September of 2007,

00:59.960 --> 01:02.840
Dr. Turner killed his wife,
Jennifer Turner,

01:03.080 --> 01:05.519
and several months after the killing,

01:05.600 --> 01:08.560
Dr. Turner was indicted by
the Davie County grand jury

01:08.640 --> 01:09.840
for first-degree murder.

01:09.920 --> 01:14.480
What did Dr. Turner say had happened
between him and his wife?

01:14.560 --> 01:19.120
Well, the killing occurred
in an outbuilding of the property

01:19.200 --> 01:21.000
that Dr. Turner and his wife

01:21.360 --> 01:26.120
had shared until they became separated,
about 18 months before the killing.

01:26.200 --> 01:28.280
And inside the building

01:28.360 --> 01:31.200
were just tons of stuff lying all around.

01:31.280 --> 01:34.640
One of the things that was lying around
was a large, seven-foot...

01:34.960 --> 01:38.320
I mean, for lack of a better term,
Viking spear

01:38.400 --> 01:41.920
that had about a 16-inch blade
on the end of it

01:42.000 --> 01:44.600
and Mrs. Turner picked up the spear

01:44.680 --> 01:48.320
and attacked him with it, driving it
through his leg, near his groin,

01:48.400 --> 01:51.320
through and through twice
and stabbing him on his arm.

01:51.560 --> 01:53.760
At that point in time,
he went into his pocket.

01:53.840 --> 01:55.600
He had a pocket knife with him

01:55.720 --> 01:58.120
and he used the pocket knife
to defend himself,

01:58.200 --> 02:00.960
and in the course of doing so,
inflicted the wounds that killed her.

02:15.560 --> 02:18.480
And did he, in fact,
have wounds on his leg

02:18.560 --> 02:22.040
that were consistent with
what he had said happened?

02:22.120 --> 02:24.800
Yes, he lost about a quarter
of his blood volume

02:24.880 --> 02:28.560
and one of those wounds
was about 1.5 centimeters

02:28.640 --> 02:30.000
from his femoral artery,

02:30.080 --> 02:32.800
which they also concluded would have
killed him if it had hit him.

02:33.360 --> 02:35.680
I’ll show you
what has been marked as Exhibit 27.

02:35.760 --> 02:36.600
Thanks.

02:38.160 --> 02:42.880
What was the initial opinion
that Agent Thomas had with regard to

02:43.440 --> 02:46.400
the shirt that Dr. Turner
had been wearing?

02:46.480 --> 02:48.400
"This transfer bloodstain pattern

02:48.480 --> 02:51.760
was consistent with a bloody hand
being wiped on the surface of the shirt."

02:52.360 --> 02:53.320
Alright.

03:00.400 --> 03:02.080
What does the second report say?

03:02.160 --> 03:05.160
It says, "It is consistent
with a pointed object,

03:05.240 --> 03:08.280
consistent with a knife being wiped
on the surface of the shirt."

03:08.760 --> 03:11.960
Was there any indication
in that second report

03:12.040 --> 03:15.480
that there had been a significant change?

03:16.160 --> 03:17.720
No, there wasn’t.

03:17.800 --> 03:20.240
What Special Agent Thomas
testified about

03:20.320 --> 03:23.560
is that the SBI and Special Agent
Deaver, who was working with him,

03:23.640 --> 03:26.600
had been presented with a new scenario

03:26.960 --> 03:30.480
that, in essence, he had inflicted
those wounds on himself

03:30.560 --> 03:32.920
and entirely staged the scene.

03:33.000 --> 03:36.080
Following that, they,
when looking at the shirt,

03:36.160 --> 03:40.040
"Could it possibly have been because
somebody was wiping a knife on the shirt?"

03:40.600 --> 03:44.640
Was that what he got out of
that meeting that Agent Deaver attended?

03:44.720 --> 03:46.480
- Yes.
- And then it says,

03:46.560 --> 03:50.560
"I’m going to meet with Duane
to do the actual reconstruction."

03:50.640 --> 03:51.600
Yes.

03:57.160 --> 03:59.520
- Who’s filming this?
- Special Agent Deaver.

04:00.000 --> 04:02.720
- He’s present there? Alright.
- He’s filming it, yes.

04:05.840 --> 04:08.400
I think what they
were trying to do is

04:08.680 --> 04:12.400
put blood on just the outside layers
of the knife

04:13.000 --> 04:14.760
in the hopes that it would somehow

04:14.880 --> 04:17.839
duplicate the initial stain, even though

04:17.920 --> 04:20.720
he didn't know of a scenario where
that would occur in actual real life,

04:20.800 --> 04:23.680
where you only have blood
on the absolute edges of a knife.

04:25.560 --> 04:27.040
Nice, good curve.

04:27.240 --> 04:28.440
Turn your wrist in.

04:29.840 --> 04:32.480
Oh, even better. Yeah, that's good.

04:33.200 --> 04:35.040
Alright, then you want to get some...

04:35.120 --> 04:37.920
just apply it on the fingers,
and just kind of...

04:40.200 --> 04:41.520
Up, up.

04:42.440 --> 04:43.480
Beautiful.

04:45.000 --> 04:46.160
That’s a wrap, baby.

04:46.640 --> 04:49.160
Not in any effort to recreate

04:49.240 --> 04:53.080
any scenario of what
actually happened that night,

04:53.440 --> 04:55.800
but just to create a stain

04:55.880 --> 04:59.640
that might look like another stain,
that might refute

05:00.080 --> 05:02.520
what our experts said about
what that stain was.

05:03.560 --> 05:05.560
There’s a bloodstain expert,
Stewart James.

05:05.640 --> 05:08.200
He’s universally regarded as one of the...

05:08.760 --> 05:11.840
handful, top two or three experts
in this field.

05:12.520 --> 05:14.960
He takes that... the video

05:15.440 --> 05:17.720
of the Kirk Turner blood experiments

05:17.800 --> 05:21.160
where Gerald Thomas wipes the shirt
and Duane Deaver is filming it,

05:21.560 --> 05:24.120
and he shows this video...

05:24.600 --> 05:29.040
uh, at professional conferences,
both in the United States and abroad.

05:29.440 --> 05:33.960
And the reaction in the community
of bloodstain pattern analysis,

05:34.560 --> 05:36.400
is... he says, it's shock.

05:36.560 --> 05:39.280
That everyone just looks
at these experiments and says,

05:39.480 --> 05:41.400
"That is a bunch of malarkey."

05:41.480 --> 05:44.000
It’s sort of what’s happening
in Mike Peterson’s

05:44.800 --> 05:47.000
motion for appropriate relief right now.

05:47.320 --> 05:50.200
You can, sort of, know
all of these anecdotal things,

05:50.280 --> 05:52.760
and you can experience them
in individual cases,

05:52.840 --> 05:55.360
like we did with Dr. Turner
and other cases,

05:55.640 --> 06:00.080
but once you see
all of those things synthesized

06:00.480 --> 06:04.600
and brought together
and woven into the same tapestry,

06:05.120 --> 06:07.640
it's pretty devastating to see,

06:08.040 --> 06:12.920
you know, what can pass for science
and justice in a courtroom.

06:15.520 --> 06:18.000
Thanks, we appreciate it.

06:19.760 --> 06:22.400
We're going to get lunch today, Deputy?

06:22.560 --> 06:24.120
We're working on it, Mike.

06:24.200 --> 06:27.760
What? This woman stabbed him
with a spear

06:27.840 --> 06:29.560
and then he cut her throat with...

06:29.640 --> 06:31.680
you know, this is not a good marriage.

06:33.080 --> 06:36.880
But anyway, but then when I read
that he...

06:37.080 --> 06:40.040
Duane Deaver believed
the man had taken a spear

06:40.320 --> 06:42.480
and put it through his leg.

06:42.880 --> 06:44.360
Man, I mean, it just

06:44.880 --> 06:49.160
boggles the mind to think that
anybody would come up with that.

06:53.240 --> 06:54.400
I got an orange.

06:59.560 --> 07:00.520
God!

07:03.760 --> 07:06.880
Yeah, feel how cool the sandwich is.
Just feel...

07:07.600 --> 07:08.760
feel how cold that is.

07:16.320 --> 07:17.480
Hm.

07:22.160 --> 07:23.560
Mm.

07:26.400 --> 07:28.800
Mrs. Sutton,
have you been qualified

07:28.880 --> 07:33.000
as an expert witness in the field
of bloodstain pattern analysis?

07:33.080 --> 07:34.040
Yes, sir, I have.

07:34.120 --> 07:39.280
I want to show you what Mr. Deaver
testified to at Mr. Peterson’s trial.

07:40.560 --> 07:42.160
I’m gonna ask for you to describe

07:42.240 --> 07:44.640
the types of experiments that you used

07:44.720 --> 07:48.680
and what the results were, generally.

07:49.120 --> 07:52.160
Test One was to place a source of blood

07:52.280 --> 07:56.680
a certain distance above the horizontal...
or above the ground,

07:56.840 --> 07:59.200
impact it with test shoes on,

07:59.320 --> 08:01.400
and to take a look at those spatters

08:01.520 --> 08:05.720
to determine if they were comparable
to what I found on the real shoes.

08:05.800 --> 08:06.640
Okay.

08:31.240 --> 08:32.760
But the wearer of these shoes,

08:33.240 --> 08:36.240
these shoes were actually
directly below

08:36.600 --> 08:40.720
a source of blood, which my opinion
is the back of the head of the victim,

08:41.039 --> 08:42.360
when it was impacted.

08:43.360 --> 08:46.320
Is there anything about
the experiments that you saw

08:46.840 --> 08:49.360
that in any way supports

08:49.840 --> 08:52.040
- Mr. Deaver’s opinion?
- No.

08:53.080 --> 08:55.320
The experiment won’t show that at all.

08:55.880 --> 09:00.320
What the experiment shows
is that if you impact a sponge,

09:00.680 --> 09:02.160
it’ll create spatter.

09:02.560 --> 09:05.360
That’s... that’s a given in my field.

09:05.920 --> 09:07.440
That’s a recreation.

09:07.720 --> 09:11.200
That’s trying to make
a set of circumstances

09:11.280 --> 09:13.960
and get a desired outcome.

09:14.360 --> 09:18.280
It’s not what I would classify
as an experiment.

10:05.640 --> 10:07.480
The opinion is that these pants

10:07.560 --> 10:09.960
are consistent with impact spatters,

10:10.040 --> 10:12.080
with a result of a forceful impact,

10:12.640 --> 10:16.040
and that the individual wearing
these pants at the time of that impact

10:16.120 --> 10:20.400
was in close proximity to the source
of blood when it was impacted.

10:21.000 --> 10:24.520
Was that experiment
that you just saw acceptable

10:24.600 --> 10:28.320
within the bounds
of bloodstain pattern analysis?

10:28.560 --> 10:31.760
No. The first thing
that really struck me was,

10:32.200 --> 10:37.280
as soon as he stepped into the stairway,
he pulled the short leg open.

10:37.680 --> 10:42.760
That’s not fair. If the question is,
"Can I take a step into the stairwell,

10:42.840 --> 10:46.360
hit somebody, and get spatter
back into my shorts,"

10:46.640 --> 10:50.400
then I have to do it
with as natural a motion as possible.

10:50.720 --> 10:52.600
One thing I did notice,

10:52.720 --> 10:57.600
the target was placed more towards
the center of the landing

10:57.680 --> 11:02.680
as opposed back where the area
of origin was actually calculated.

11:02.760 --> 11:06.240
And, of course, that’s so that
you can have one leg up.

11:06.400 --> 11:09.080
That certainly could be
one explanation, sure.

11:09.160 --> 11:12.360
If it was back further,
somebody'd be standing on the landing,

11:12.480 --> 11:14.640
they wouldn’t have their leg up,
would they?

11:14.720 --> 11:18.000
I agree with that and it would also be
difficult to hit that sponge.

11:19.040 --> 11:20.760
Are the experiments that you used

11:20.840 --> 11:24.560
consistent with
what others in the field use

11:24.640 --> 11:27.480
to conduct analysis
of bloodstain pattern...

11:27.560 --> 11:29.120
- Yes. Yes, they are.
- ...examinations?

11:29.200 --> 11:34.480
Is it consistent with the methodology
that you learned 15, 16 years ago?

11:34.560 --> 11:35.760
Yes, it is.

11:37.000 --> 11:38.920
- Is that true?
- No, sir.

11:39.400 --> 11:43.360
Is his methodology, as you saw
in these experiments, what others,

11:43.720 --> 11:47.120
who are competent in the field
of bloodstain pattern analysis use

11:47.280 --> 11:49.640
- to analyze crime scenes?
- No, sir.

11:50.160 --> 11:51.000
No, sir.

11:56.320 --> 11:57.160
Hey!

11:58.920 --> 12:00.120
Happy birthday.

12:01.880 --> 12:03.400
